Exploring scraped immowelt.de Apartment data for North Rhine-Westphalia (May 2022)¶

Author: Michael Volk

Introduction¶

In this Jupyter-Notebook scraped and prepared apartment-exposes-data for buy & rent from immowelt.de for the german federal state North Rhine-Westphalia as of May 2022 is explored. For the exploration descriptive statistics techniques like univariate and multivariate analysis are used. Also geographic analysis regarding prices per area in North Rhine Westphalia and regarding rent-to-buy-price-ratio is performed.

This Jupyter-Notebook is part of my project: micvolk.github.io/Buy-and-Rent-Price-Estimator-for-Apartments
Visit the website and get a detailed description of the project steps - starting from scraping, preparing and exploring the data from immowelt.de, evaluating different machine learning models and ending with transferring the best model into production by building a Web-App.
To use the Web-App please follow this link: price-estimator-apartment-nrw.herokuapp.com

Previous steps with own developed Python-modules¶

  • scraping.py: apartment-expose-data has been scraped from immowelt.de in May 2022 with an own built web-scraper. The scraped data includes apartment-exposes in german state North Rhine-Westphalia for buy and for rent - the exposes-data has been saved as pandas-dataframes (pickled in csv-files) - one for buy and one for rent.
  • cleaning.py: Scraped data has been cleaned (dropping apartments which did not match certain conditions and dropping useless features)
  • featureEngineering.py: Cleaned data has been feature-engineered (mapping of values, extracting information from apartment-description text, ...) and saved as pandas-dataframes (pickled in csv-files) - one for buy and one for rent.

Sources¶

The 2 generated csv-files of featureEngineering.py and a shapefile-map of North rhine-westphalia are the sources for this Jupyter-Notebook:

  • featureEngineered_buy.csv
  • featureEngineered_rent.csv
  • shapefiles\dvg2gem_nw.shp (Source: https://www.opengeodata.nrw.de/produkte/geobasis/vkg/dvg/dvg2/)

Sections¶

  • First look on buy- & rent-dataframe
  • Univariate Analysis

Explanations:

  • Price variables are denominated in
  • 'Area' is measured in square-metres
  • Variables with prefix 'EQ_' (stands for apartment-equipment) can only take the values:
    • 1: 'Yes'
    • 0: 'No'
  • Subsequent prefixes of variables with prefix 'EQ_' can be:
    • 'CAT_': stands for apartment-category
    • 'CON_': stands for apartment-condition
    • 'OUT_': stands for apartment-outdoor-equipment
  • 'Url' links to the original apartment-expose of immowelt.de
  • 'geometry' contains the information of the variables 'Latitude' & 'Longitude' converted to the coordinate-reference-system epsg:25832

Histograms regarding columns with numeric values¶

Results:

  • Distributions of the price variables have a positive skew (=right-skewed) for buy & rent, so the mean-value is skewed to the right of the center of the data. That is not surprising as income and fortune distribution are typical examples for right-skewed distributions - and it seems to be obvious that apartment-prices are strongly positve correlated with income and fortune
  • Also not surprisingly the 'Area' and 'Rooms' variables are right-skewed for buy & rent
  • As a consequence of the right-skewness of the Price-, Area-, and Rooms-variables a normalization (via log-transform) will be performed for them in the next step to get a distribution which is more similiar to a normal-distribution - that helps for prediction with linear regression models in later steps
  • Many relative old apartments are offered for buy and rent (big share of apartments with construction year between 1950 and 1970)
  • Isolated distribution of Latitude or Longitude does not make much sense => combinated distribution can be seen on geographic map in section Geographic Analysis

Histograms regarding log-transformed Price-, Area-, and Rooms-variables¶

Results:

  • Distributions of the log-transformed Price-, Area-, and Rooms-variables are much more similiar to a normal-distribution than without normalization - that helps for prediction with linear regression models in later steps.

Results:

  • The correlation of the price variables against the other variables has a very similiar pattern for buy & rent:
    • Strongly positve correlated with 'Area'
    • positive correlated with 'Rooms', 'ConstructionYear', 'EQ_CAT_maisonette', 'EQ_CAT_penthouse', 'EQ_CON_firstOccupancy', 'EQ_CON_upscale', 'EQ_OUT_terrace'

Barplots regarding price-variable against apartment-equipment variables¶

Median price of apartment with value = 1 (='Yes') compared to value = 0 (='No') for each apartment-equipment variable.
Hint: The vertical mini-bar on top of each bar represents the 95% confidence-interval generated by random-sampling (longer mini-bar means higher uncertainty).

Results:

As already indicated by the correlation-heatmap shown before, the barplots visualise that:

  • Apartments with categories like 'maisonette', 'penthouse' or 'terraceApartment' have clearly higher median value prices
  • Apartments with conditions like 'firstOccupancy' or 'upscale' have clearly higher median value prices
  • Apartments with 'terrace' have clearly higher median value prices

Results:

  • Similiar pattern regarding the geographic distribution of apartments and prices per area (log-scaled) for buy & rent:

Correlation of Rent-cold to Buy-price ratio in relation to buy- and rent-price¶

    Rent_cold_to_Buy_price_ratio
Buy_price_per_Area median -0.82
Rent_cold_per_Area median -0.61
Rent_cold_to_Buy_price_ratio 1.00

Results:¶

  • Cities differ in their Rent-cold to Buy-price ratio
  • Rent-cold to Buy-price ratio has negative correlation with Buy_price_per_Area and Rent_cold_per_Area => expensive cities tend to have a low Rent-cold to Buy-price ratio and cheap cities tend to have a high Rent-cold to Buy-price ratio
  • But there are also cities deviating from this relationship, like Remscheid and Solingen: no expensive city in terms of Buy_price_per_Area and Rent_cold_per_Area, but low Rent-cold to Buy-price ratio
  • Simple interpretation: It is better to rent in cities with low Rent-cold to Buy-price ratio (like Aachen and Dsseldorf) and it is better to buy in cities with high Rent-cold to Buy-price ratio (like Gelsenkirchen and Duisburg)
  • Advanced interpretation in the framework of the efficient-market hypothesis combined with the Gordon growth model: There is no advantage, but also no disadvantage, to rent in cities with low Rent-cold to Buy-price ratio and vice versa because the apartment market is efficient so that there is no arbitrage-opportunity. Cities with low Rent-cold to buy-price ratio are expected to have higher future rent growth rates compared to cities with high Rent-cold to buy-price ratio => the simple interpretation can be misleading as it does not consider future rent growth rates.
